<h2>Scale you can feel — the numbers that didn't make the headline</h2>

<ul>
  <li>A typical ChatGPT-style text query is about 200 times more energy-intensive than a spam-filter check. (p. 9)</li>
  <li>Generating one AI image takes about 2.9 Wh — and a water footprint of about two tablespoons (29 mL). (p. 9)</li>
  <li>One high-complexity AI video clip draws more than 415 Wh, with a water footprint of 4.1 liters — almost a two-day drinking water need for one person. (p. 9)</li>
  <li>Training GPT-4 used roughly 600 million liters of water — about 237 Olympic-sized pools. (p. 8)</li>
  <li>By 2030, AI infrastructure could generate up to 2.5 million metric tons of e-waste per year — nearly 250 Eiffel Towers, every year. (p. 10)</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Notice what the report did</div>
  <p>Page 11 of the report carries an AI-generated illustration — and directly beneath it, this disclosure: "AI-generated conceptual image of AI's environmental footprint, generated using OpenAI's ChatGPT/DALL·E, May 2026. Estimated footprints per standard-resolution AI image: 2.9 Wh electricity, 1.22 g CO₂e, 28.6 mL of water, and 0.45 cm² of land."</p>
  <p>The UN used AI to make an image, said so, and told you exactly what it cost. Keep that move in mind — you'll meet it again in Block 3.</p>
</div>

<h2>Questions to bring to class</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Who wrote this, and for whom? (Check the authors and the institute — then check who funds it.)</li>
  <li>AP wrote "more than all but 10 countries." The report says "would rank 11th." Same fact — does it feel the same?</li>
  <li>What can't this report know? (Hint: it says its own data-center figures depend on what companies disclose.)</li>
</ol>

